en to twenty hours without any rest for her. Although she was born in 1953 as a low-caste girl in a South Indian fishing village, today millions revere her as guru and goddess, a living embodiment of the divine on earth. Reflections of Amma focuses on communities of Amma’s devotees in the United States, showing how they endeavor to mirror their guru’s behaviors and transform themselves to emulate the ethos of the movement. This study argues that "inheritors" and "adopters" of Hindu traditions differently interpret Hindu goddesses, Amma, and her relation to feminism and women’s empowerment because of their inherited religious, cultural, and political dispositions. In this insightful ethnographic analysis, Amanda J. Lucia discovers how the politics of American multiculturalism reifies these cultural differences in "de facto congregations," despite the fact that Amma’s embrace attempts to erase communal boundaries in favor of global unity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh  aamma.  acaste system.  acomparative religion.  acultural anthropology.  acultural studies.  adarshan programs.  adivine figure.  aembrace.  aempowerment.  aethnographers.  aethnographic analysis.  afeminism.  afishing village.  agender studies.  aglobal unity.  aguru.  ahindu goddesses.  ahindu traditions.  ahugging saint.  ahugs.  ahumanitarianism.  aliving goddess.  amata amritanandamayi.  amulticulturalism.  apersonal transformation.  areligious figures.  asouth india.  atransnational organizations.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028114140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095807440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958074423C